### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Angular has a magnificent template syntax. While it is not imaginative as JSX, the performance benefits make it worth the while.

What Angular Templates limit us to, is a strict dependence on the Angular Compiler. There is no escape hatch to native Javascript; I propose determining a syntax which would make this possible.

Consider how Angular developers have to do double the work to access an application constant, compared to React or Vue developers:

## React

#### app-settings.js
````jsx

export const AppName = 'Sample React App';

````
#### app.jsx
````jsx

import { AppName } from './app-settings.js';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(<h1>Hello, world, from { AppName } </h1>);

````

## Angular

#### app-settings.ts
````ts

export const AppName = 'Sample Angular App';

````

#### app.component.ts
````ts
import { AppName } from './app-settings';

@Component({
  standalone: true,
  selector: 'app',
  template: `
  <h1>Hello, world, from {{ AppName }} </h1>
  `
})
export class AppComponent {
  AppName = AppName
}
````

It's that extra binding, AppName = AppName, that can get tedious. 

It also forces dependency injection to be used _everywhere_ in a component. That's great for library development, but sometimes your constants are just your constants. Javascript already gives us a module system for shipping things around - can we remove that final "import it into Angular land" step, and just allow templates to access them directly?



### Proposed solution

Introduce another class of Angular Expression which would be considered a **native expression**. Initially, I propose that we disallow the use of pipes for these expressions, though I'm sure they could be worked back in.

For backwards compatability, a **native expression** would likely need to have `{{{ }}}` as its nomenclature.

# Native Expressions

Native Expressions inject native javascript with minimal transformations into the final Ivy view engine instruction set.

Native Expressions cannot do the following: 
 - Use the `export` keyword
 - Use the `class` keyword
 - Use `const`, `let`, `for`, `while`, or other control flow
 - Use `import()`

Native Expressions can do the following:
 - Use static `import` in the first native expression of an Angular template document
 - Reference component via `this`
 - Call functions (use at your own risk)
 - Access ambient variables in the scope of the template.
 
 
## What are some sample templates which use Native Expressions?


## Raw Expression Sample

#### app-settings.ts
````ts

export const AppName = 'Sample Angular App';

````

#### app.component.ts
````ts
import { AppName } from './app-settings';

@Component({
  standalone: true,
  selector: 'app',
  template: `
  <h1>Hello, world, from {{{ AppName }}} </h1>
  `
})
export class AppComponent {
}
````

#### Demonstrating import from a template.html file
````html
{{{
import { AppName } from './app.constants';
}}}
<h1>Hello world from {{AppName}}!</h1>
````

#### Using native expressions as inputs
````ts

import { AppName } from './app-settings';

@Component({
  template: `
<textarea placeholder="Say Something about {{{ AppName }}}"></textarea>
  `
})
export class SampleComponent {}

````

#### Using native expressions as inputs - square bracket syntax
````html
{{{
import { defaultConnectedPositions } from './app-constants';
}}}
<textarea [placeholder]="{{{ AppName }}}"></textarea>
````

````
#### Using getter functions - no integration with Change Detection!
````html
{{{
import { getAppName } from './app-constants';
}}}
<h1>Hi from {{{ getAppName() }}}></textarea>
````

## How do Native Expressions integrate with Ivy?

### Sample Ivy output - static values.
````
/*
All relevant imports etc. are hoisted here.
*/
import { AppName } from './app.constants';

function (renderFlags, ctx) {
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Create) {
     elementStart(0, 'h1',);
     text(1);
     elementEnd();
  }
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Update) {
    advance(1);
    textInterpolate1('Hello world from ', AppName, '!');
  }
}

````

### Sample Ivy output - using function invocation
````
/*
All relevant imports etc. are hoisted here.
*/
import { getAppName } from './app.constants';

function (renderFlags, ctx) {
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Create) {
     elementStart(0, 'h1',);
     text(1);
     elementEnd();
  }
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Update) {
    advance(1);
    textInterpolate1('Hello world from ', getAppName(), '!');
  }
}

````

### Alternatives considered

We can keep doing things that class-based "Angular Way". I don't have much of a choice - we've invested thousands of hours into the product and Angular is "good enough" that there's no reason to abandon it in a rewrite.

That said - we need to find ways to get Angular out of the way. Maybe something like Native Expressions, allowing raw Javascript to take center stage, would be one way to simplify things.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

service-worker

### Description

When using ignoreSearch=true my Angular app became extremly slow showing image galleries, but only for my Chrome users. I have SAS tokens in the query params, who changes frequently. Unfortunately it is a very old known problem (Ref.: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=682677). hash for full url are saved in index, so when using ignoreSearch=true, every index needs to be checked, not effective and gives poor performance.

E.g. of datagroup
`"dataGroups": [
    {
        "name": "dynamicResources",
        "urls": [
            "**XXX/**"
        ],
        "cacheConfig": {
            "maxSize": 2000,
            "maxAge": "30d",
            "strategy": "performance"
        },
        "cacheQueryOptions": {
            "ignoreSearch": true
        }
    }
]`

### Proposed solution

Is it possible to create an option which causes the query parameters in urls for data groups to be completely ignored, so they are stored without and retrieved without and we keep the good performance?

### Alternatives considered

If not an option, then a workaround where you can overwrite ngsw-worker.js until Chrome is fixed.

